[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Uh sure... I'll arrange that.[[/span]] She looked up at the starry endless ceiling taking a deep breath.

Hege turned back to Alva Prime, treading the emptiness of the void as if she were swimming in water. "Uhm, the fragment that you came from took a name, did you have one when you awoke from your slumber?" Hege asked, as time advances.

[[span style="color:green"]]//"No. We were never so vain as to name ourselves, nor was there anything or anyone there at the beginning to title us. However, your people,"//[[/span]] she said, reaching out across the void, arm stretching impossibly far to gently poke Hege who follows the approaching finger and resists the temptation to bite at it,  [[span style="color:green"]]//"were the first to give me a name. A fitting and simple name."//[[/span]] Alva Prime then looked at Hege as if she were a mother having a conversation  with a daughter who has made her immensely proud.

Hege's solemn gaze breaks into a small warm smile. "I'm glad that we could do that for you." 

Sherry glanced between them, eyebrows half raised, and interjects. [[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Erm, so all the representations, and what you look like right now are all really human based... are they your true shape? Like, is this what you actually look like?"[[/span]] 

A laugh escaped her lips. In a flash flesh began to bubble and twist, inflating outwards, dozens of eyes pushing out into many yellow orbs of flesh, hundreds of legs, claws, tentacles, spheres, all centered around four terrible but kind yellow spheres. 

Instant regret flashed across Sherry's face, in addition to a yelp. 

As quickly as she changed, she returned to normal.

A moment of recovery passed, before Hege asked a question. "I understand why the uh, larger you, seeded you... but why are you a fragment of her, and not a fragment of the whole? That's where I'm lost... and maybe I don't know the history as well as I should."

Alva sighed, and clapped her hands together as the landscape changed again back to the split open cocoon where she sleeps. Shadow figures quietly approached, horrible dark chains grasped in their many undefined limbs. 

"Who i-" Hege was interrupted by the gruesome wrapping of chains around The Progenitor's sleeping form, waking her violently but far too slowly to prevent the gleaming orbs and undulating chains of malice from searing into her astral flesh as she silently screamed. 

The [[[SCP-3230 | chainmaker]]] cowered behind the other figures, hooking the ends of each link into the great crushing voids of many event horizons, pinning her.  [[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Awful, horrible. I can't even imagine. Ugh."[[/span]] Now fully bound, she still managed to wrap inconceivably many great limbs around the great eel as it attempted to drain her thoughts, and ripped his mind from his essence and cast it into the great maw where it was obliterated, leaving him a spineless, empty, hungry husk. In the final moments as the chainmaker desperately wound his horrible implements around the great void, she managed to rip one of infinitely many limbs from her body, and flung it into the void. Alva prime swam after it, Hege and Sherry following.

Hege attempted to find words, she really did, but none would come. Nothing could describe the horrible sorrow in her heart at this cruel act.

[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"These other shadows, these //monsters//, they are like you? Were there others? Friends?"[[/span]]

[[span style="color:green"]]//"There were 13 of us at the beginning."//[[/span]] A series of intense images sprung into being as they swam after the floating arm. [[footnote]]She appears first, standing tall and proud without chains. Colorful scriptic text in green appears next to her. [[span style="color:green"]] The Progenitor, first and eldest of those descended from the astral plane. Stripped of power by star filled chains. The one they fear. [[/span]][[/footnote]]^^,^^[[footnote]]Second came a terrible figure, tall and masculine, angry and wielding a great trident with purple and blue tattoos swirling across his form. Purple text appeared next to him: [[span style="color:purple"]]The Tyrant, master of unbridled hate, envious of mortal life, conjurer of unholy storms. Sealed beneath the watching stones underneath the Orkney sky.[[/span]][[/footnote]]^^,^^[[footnote]]Third a great thing made of gears and metal came into focus, twitching with every second. Gold text appears next to them [[span style="color:gold"]]Clockworks, founder of machine and gears, metal of heart. Forever broken by a war with her lover.[[/span]][[/footnote]]^^,^^[[footnote]]Fourth came the Dragon of flesh, great devourer of worlds, who trailed life on that which they did not eat. Next to them in brown text  [[span style="color:brown"]]Trapped within the heart of his lover. Feared, revered, and hated by those shapers of flesh, for its unbridled power.[[/span]][[/footnote]]^^,^^[[footnote]] Fifth came a starfish with five terrible arms stretching into every conceivable direction.[[/footnote]]^^,^^[[footnote]] Sixth came one of carnal sin, and terrible pain. In red text next to them it read [[span style="color:red"]]The red shah upon the sands around that great place at the end of the world. Imprisoned before time itself, his red threads worming their way into that once great place of Alagadda, rending its parting.[[/span]][[/footnote]]

[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Ok. OK! Jesus, my brain can't handle all of that at once."[[/span]]

Alva simply shrugged as they swam. [[span style="color:green"]]//"You asked."//[[/span]]

"Which one is the chainmaker?" Hege asked, swimming alongside a pod of winged serpents. The serpents scattered as the menacing shadows streaked behind still, chasing the arm. The arm slowly took on the familiar four eyed humanoid shape.

[[span style="color:green"]]//"#13."//[[/span]] She said bitterly. [[span style="color:green"]]//"He's the only one who has never set foot on your planet."//[[/span]]

[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"With all due respect, and to get off the topic of primordial gods that make my brain want to scream, why Earth? Why not some other planet?"[[/span]] Sherry asked, trying her damndest to ignore the shadows behind them.

She laughed sadly. [[span style="color:green"]]//"Are you wondering if there is something special about your world? If there is something incidentally important that lead me here?"//[[/span]] She paused to consider as they chased the goddess fragment through the cosmos. The shape of a familiar galaxy approached, faster and faster, then a spiral arm, and then a nebula. Then rocketing past Pluto, then Neptune, then Uranus, Saturn, Jupiter, Mars, the Moon, and finally, the blue speck as the goddess fragment smashed into Earth, over what will become the Yucatan Penninsula. 

[[span style="color:green"]]//"I would love to tell you that all of this was because your little blue planet was of grave importance, that these primordial beings came here because they revered or reviled your existence. But it's not. It's because they fear us, even in our fragmented and bound state, they fear what we are, they fear what we can do."//[[/span]] She turned in the air towards Sherry and Hege, as the shockwave spread across Earth's surface, the great monstrous entities hovering above it, waiting. [[span style="color:green"]]//"And they are right to be afraid, because we will personally savage and grind the nine who bound us in those cursed chains into oblivion."//[[/span]] Her arms raise, held wide. Seven enormous pillars of molten earth and boiling water reached into space from below, as the chainmaker hung farther back around the moon, and then fled as seven of his conspirators are dragged towards the planet's surface.

There's an extended moment of silence, where a pen could drop and be as loud as an airplane.

The redhead glanced down at her watch, noting the time and that they have about 20 minutes until the performance ends in the split causality, [[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"We only have a few more minutes and I have so many questions, but there are some really important ones to ask first."[[/span]] 

Alva Prime looked to her with tired yellow eyes, waiting. 

[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Why the Glyden Barn? What about them is so special, why is it always them who defeats Teran in your scripts, that breaks the chains that bind you? Why is it them that saves the us, the veil, and Earth. Why not someone else?"[[/span]] 

She gently clapped her hands together, and time sped up immensely fast. The sun and moon blurred in the sky as they rocketed forward in time, coming to a sudden and slightly nauseating halt over the Islands of Orkney. [[span style="color:green"]]//"5000 years ago, we stood with the Finnfolk at the battle of Orkney, where fought that bastard Teran. We expended so much energy that we were forced to slumber for 4900 years... and even with the fully realized potential of my partner and mother of my child, we only just barely sealed Teran."//[[/span]] A long pause, as she gathered her breath, half choking. [[span style="color:green"]]//"But she gave herself to keep him sealed, because it wasn't enough to keep him down."// [[/span]] Triemedes is visible below giving a past version of Alva one last hug, before a great purple orb of light enveloped her, and she ripped through time and space out of view. [[span style="color:green"]]//"And she still wasn't able to hold him. And now the Orkney seal is a ticking time bomb. Only a daughter of mine who can access all of me, chained or not, can do what you need. That is why the Glyden Barn is so important. Only they can slay Teran, sever my chains, and save your world."//[[/span]]

"Will... you tell us who it is? Who the Glyden Barn will be... is it destined to be my child, or a future child?" Hege asked softly, earnestly, unconsciously making herself small.

[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"That might be beyond what she's able to say your maj-"[[/span]] a pause. [[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Hege."[[/span]] She gently placed a hand on the Finnfolk's shoulder as the three of them drifted down and set foot on the flat earth of the Orkney landscape.

Alva Prime gently brought her hands together and placed fingers to her lips, rocking on her heels before folding her fingers inwards and pointing at Hege, softness in her golden eyes.  [[span style="color:green"]]//"Oh child. You haven't figured it out yet? Think of all the suffering you've been through. [[[Where There is Desire There is Gonna be a Flame
|Nearly burning alive in the royal library]]].//"[[/span]] The environment shifted around them to the raging inferno of the Royal Library as Hege is dragged from the rubble by a strange four eyed aquatic feline. Sherry looked around, eyes wide.

[[span style="color:green"]]//"Locked in a dark dungeon, hungry, tired, cold and alone for more than a century."//[[/span]] Another shift in perspective to a dark, dank, and narrow cell with only the glow of dim rustic that a younger Hege had drawn in the sand. 

[[span style="color:green"]]//"To watching your people be savaged, brutalized, and devastated due to the actions of your captor. Yet you endured, confronted your demons in the sands of Libya, and lead your people with intelligence, integrity, and courage beyond compare into a new golden age of knowledge and growth."//[[/span]] Alva points again. [[span style="color:green"]]//"You are the Glyden Barn, and you are... destined to do many great things my child."//[[/span]]

Hege looked down, balling her fists before unclinching them. Her brow wrinkled as she looked back up, confusion and conflicted emotion in her eyes. [[span style="color:blue"]]"I-I-I'm the Glyden Barn?"[[/span]]  She takes a step slightly back, and looks down again before up, voice cracking. [[span style="color:blue"]]"But I don't even... feel like a Queen. I've been weak, helpless, and nothing I do feels as if it is right or strong. I can't be here. She's a hero and I'm simply not."[[/span]]

Alva Prime's eyes softened. [[span style="color:green"]]//"Oh child. Even Gilgamesh didn't reach Enkidu in the underworld in four years. You are loved, and you will be loved, and will love. Doubt is natural, but you are you and everything will work out."//[[/span]][[footnote]][[span style="color:green"]]//"I promised I wouldn't cry. This is a mortal thing. I promised I wouldn't cry."//[[/span]][[/footnote]]

Sherry gently placed a supporting hand on Hege's shoulder, as the Queen looked down again at her hands, processing and holding back tears. 

[[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"We're running up on time... and I only have one more question."[[/span]] Sherry said softly. [[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Why us? Why of all the attempts to ask you anything meaningful, you decide to respond to us. I mean, besides the obvious of her being the Glyden Barn.[[/span]]

Alva Prime's eyes started watering. [[span style="color:green"]]//"Well. Sherry Andrews, O5-01-03. Just as Hege Aquailian has endured hardship you have as well. Orphaned by parents you'll never know, [[[All in All You're Just A 'Nother Brick in the Wall | manipulated by and deceived by a man you considered a friend and a mentor.]]] You've rose in spite of every challenge, every roadblock. I admire perseverence and genuine kindness in humans, even if your species has caused me more trouble than I care to remember."//[[/span]] 

There's a long pause as she wiped her eyes. [[span style="color:green"]]//"Besides, I owe you a monumental debt of gratitude."//[[/span]] 

Sherry blinked three times, glancing at her watch, a minute and 30 seconds left. [[span style="font-family:cavolini"]]"Huh!? What, why?"[[/span]] 

Alva Prime smiled, and slowly changed shape until she had taken on the form of Astrid the Kind, former Queen of the Finnfolk. [[span style="color:green"]]//"Because, you gave me an opportunity I didn't get with my first child, who was carted to safety and grew up, ruled, and died before I woke from slumber."//[[/span]] She stepped forward and stood in front of Hege, looking at her once more in the way only a proud and loving mother can. She hugged her.

[[span style="color:green"]]//"You could have brought any Finnfolk scholar, but you brought my second daughter. You gave me three hours to be a mom for the first time."//[[/span]] The goddess cried, tears dripping onto the floor behind hege, tragically beautiful flowers sprouting at their feet.

[[span style="color:green"]]//"I just wish I had more ti-//"[[/span]] Then, without a bang, without a flash, she was simply gone, as causality peeled back to normal. 

Hege Aquailian, Queen of the Finnfolk found herself in Carnegie hall next to O5-01-03 Sherry Andrews, with tears streaming down her face, legs trembling. Security personnel and Royal guards suddenly rushed to them.

[[span style="color:blue"]]"Mom?"[[/span]]
 _
 _
{{End Log}}
